It certainly wasn't
at the start.

46
00:06:15,943 --> 00:06:17,843
And, now that we're here...

47
00:06:17,845 --> 00:06:19,144
- It was <i>strongly</i> suggested.

48
00:06:19,146 --> 00:06:20,846
And now that
we're somehow here,

49
00:06:20,848 --> 00:06:22,114
it would seem irresponsible
to everyone involved

50
00:06:22,116 --> 00:06:24,616
to not have the discussion.

51
00:06:24,618 --> 00:06:27,452
- Right, that's...

52
00:06:27,454 --> 00:06:28,754
Exactly what I'm saying.

53
00:06:28,756 --> 00:06:31,957
- Who's the author
of the addendum?

54
00:06:31,959 --> 00:06:34,126
- I imagine
it was a compositor.

55
00:06:34,128 --> 00:06:35,827
- Right, so...

56
00:06:35,829 --> 00:06:38,130
- Wasn't me.
- Or me.

57
00:06:44,837 --> 00:06:46,104
- I'm sorry?

58
00:06:46,106 --> 00:06:47,105
- The addendum.

59
00:06:47,107 --> 00:06:48,573
- What about it?

60
00:06:48,575 --> 00:06:49,808
- We think it should be
discussed.

61
00:06:49,810 --> 00:06:51,042
- So? Discuss it.

62
00:06:51,044 --> 00:06:52,611
- Why was it included?

63
00:06:52,613 --> 00:06:54,746
- I was asked to include
applied suppositions.

64
00:06:54,748 --> 00:06:56,681
- When?
- Nine months ago.

65
00:06:56,683 --> 00:06:58,483
Why am I being interrogated?

66
00:06:58,485 --> 00:07:00,118
- Come on.

67
00:07:00,120 --> 00:07:01,553
It was always agreed on,
from the start,

68
00:07:01,555 --> 00:07:03,021
that everything
in the final report

69
00:07:03,023 --> 00:07:05,157
would be discussed
and agreed upon by all of us,

70
00:07:05,159 --> 00:07:06,491
unanimously.

71
00:07:06,493 --> 00:07:08,493
- That's right.

72
00:07:08,495 --> 00:07:09,895
- [Chuckles]

73
00:07:09,897 --> 00:07:12,063
Well...

74
00:07:12,065 --> 00:07:13,632
As--as I was saying--
- was it Von neu--

75
00:07:13,634 --> 00:07:15,100
I'm sorry to interrupt.

76
00:07:15,102 --> 00:07:17,536
Was it Von neumann who said
that in mathematics

77
00:07:17,538 --> 00:07:20,439
we don't understand things,
we simply get used to them?

78
00:07:20,441 --> 00:07:21,673
- What does that mean?

79
00:07:21,675 --> 00:07:24,976
- Well, uh...
I suppose what it means

80
00:07:24,978 --> 00:07:27,179
is that the implication
stated within the addendum

81
00:07:27,181 --> 00:07:28,613
seemed to be
a slight stretch

82
00:07:28,615 --> 00:07:32,050
for an algorithmic
theoretician,

83
00:07:32,052 --> 00:07:34,453
wouldn't you say, Jim?

84
00:07:34,455 --> 00:07:36,154
- I can't believe
the English

85
00:07:36,156 --> 00:07:38,156
still haven't taught you
proper manners.

86
00:07:38,158 --> 00:07:40,025
- Guys, let's stay
on the topic.

87
00:07:40,027 --> 00:07:41,927
- I'm not entirely sure
what that means, but, uh...

88
00:07:41,929 --> 00:07:43,829
- Oh, I'm sure you wouldn't.
- It's apparent,

89
00:07:43,831 --> 00:07:45,464
however superficially, that
you've exceeded your authority.

90
00:07:45,466 --> 00:07:46,498
- Perhaps we should hang on
for a minute--

91
00:07:46,500 --> 00:07:48,200
- this is not a democracy...

92
00:07:48,202 --> 00:07:49,601
- Actually, authority's
even the wrong word,

93
00:07:49,603 --> 00:07:50,769
because that
has implications,

94
00:07:50,771 --> 00:07:52,103
and in this case,
there are none.

95
00:07:52,105 --> 00:07:53,839
You had none.
- Or a lecture hall, son.

96
00:07:53,841 --> 00:07:55,040
- There's no point
in questioning--

97
00:07:55,042 --> 00:07:56,575
- I'm not a child.

98
00:07:56,577 --> 00:07:59,077
- No, you most certainly
are not.

99
00:07:59,079 --> 00:08:00,812
You used the word "superficial"
a moment ago,

100
00:08:00,814 --> 00:08:02,180
and if that's where
you'd like to leave it,

101
00:08:02,182 --> 00:08:03,748
then the answer
is quite simple.

102
00:08:03,750 --> 00:08:04,916
Three words:

103
00:08:04,918 --> 00:08:08,920
Knowledge is power.

104
00:08:12,658 --> 00:08:15,527
- Yes, it is.

105
00:08:15,529 --> 00:08:18,763
- His brief career
has undoubtedly touched,

106
00:08:18,765 --> 00:08:20,565
influenced,
and motivated all of us

107
00:08:20,567 --> 00:08:22,200
in some capacity.

108
00:08:22,202 --> 00:08:25,170
And these
brief introductions

109
00:08:25,172 --> 00:08:28,206
always, on some level,
seem to fall short

110
00:08:28,208 --> 00:08:30,208
of true justice.

111
00:08:30,210 --> 00:08:33,144
But, nevertheless,
here goes.

112
00:08:35,848 --> 00:08:39,751
Our honored guest was born
in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania,

113
00:08:39,753 --> 00:08:41,887
son of a banker
and a homemaker,

114
00:08:41,889 --> 00:08:44,923
a graduate of the university
of Pennsylvania,

115
00:08:44,925 --> 00:08:46,157
summa cum laude,

116
00:08:46,159 --> 00:08:48,593
before receiving his phd
in mathematics

117
00:08:48,595 --> 00:08:50,829
from Princeton.

118
00:08:50,831 --> 00:08:55,000
Based on his thesis work
on riemann's hypothesis,

119
00:08:55,002 --> 00:08:56,735
he was an invited fellow

120
00:08:56,737 --> 00:08:58,670
at the institute
for advanced study

121
00:08:58,672 --> 00:09:01,072
as well as at mit,

122
00:09:01,074 --> 00:09:04,009
where his work
on complexity theory

123
00:09:04,011 --> 00:09:06,678
earned him the Abel prize.

124
00:09:06,680 --> 00:09:10,015
He is presently the rouse ball
Professor of mathematics

125
00:09:10,017 --> 00:09:12,083
in the department
of pure mathematics

126
00:09:12,085 --> 00:09:15,954
and mathematical statistics
at Cambridge university

127
00:09:15,956 --> 00:09:19,024
and a fellow
at trinity college.

128
00:09:19,026 --> 00:09:21,660
In 2008...

129
00:09:21,662 --> 00:09:25,263
He was awarded the greatest
honor in our profession

130
00:09:25,265 --> 00:09:27,766
when he was presented
with the fields medal

131
00:09:27,768 --> 00:09:30,268
for his proof
of the nonexistence

132
00:09:30,270 --> 00:09:32,971
of one-way functions.

133
00:09:32,973 --> 00:09:34,839
Ladies and gentlemen,

134
00:09:34,841 --> 00:09:38,310
it is with great honor
that I now present to you

135
00:09:38,312 --> 00:09:40,278
Dr. Timothy horton.

136
00:09:40,280 --> 00:09:46,351
[Applause]

137
00:09:47,587 --> 00:09:50,655
[Cheers and applause]

138
00:10:01,901 --> 00:10:03,768
- Has he seen this?

139
00:10:03,770 --> 00:10:04,836
- Which part?

140
00:10:04,838 --> 00:10:06,071
- The addendum.

141
00:10:06,073 --> 00:10:08,039
- No.
What does it matter?

142
00:10:08,041 --> 00:10:11,610
- The implications
are fairly self-evident, right?

143
00:10:11,612 --> 00:10:14,212
I mean, perhaps
not through and through,

144
00:10:14,214 --> 00:10:16,081
but let's be clear.

145
00:10:16,083 --> 00:10:17,849
This endeavor
would not have received

146
00:10:17,851 --> 00:10:19,217
the level of funding
and classification

147
00:10:19,219 --> 00:10:21,319
if its implications
were not self-evident.

148
00:10:21,321 --> 00:10:22,921
- I agree
they're self-evident,

149
00:10:22,923 --> 00:10:25,256
but I still feel
they need to be aired,

150
00:10:25,258 --> 00:10:27,626
and I guess, mulled over.

151
00:10:27,628 --> 00:10:29,327
I don't know,
I feel uncomfortable

152
00:10:29,329 --> 00:10:31,296
to just sit here
with assumptions.

153
00:10:31,298 --> 00:10:33,264
We all know
this is far too big

154
00:10:33,266 --> 00:10:34,833
to assume anything.

155
00:10:34,835 --> 00:10:36,201
- Why is it self-evident?

156
00:10:36,203 --> 00:10:37,869
- Pardon me?

157
00:10:37,871 --> 00:10:39,838
- Why is it self-evident?

158
00:10:39,840 --> 00:10:43,074
- Well, I mean...

159
00:10:43,076 --> 00:10:45,377
You don't work
your entire academic life

160
00:10:45,379 --> 00:10:47,245
in the fields of theoretical
computer science

161
00:10:47,247 --> 00:10:50,348
and complexity theory
without understanding the--

162
00:10:50,350 --> 00:10:52,951
the massive implications
of doing something like this.

163
00:10:52,953 --> 00:10:55,420
- Right.

164
00:10:55,422 --> 00:10:57,922
Well, I guess, uh,
I guess I feel

165
00:10:57,924 --> 00:10:59,891
there are two things wrong
with what you just said.

166
00:10:59,893 --> 00:11:04,195
Um, first of all, we were
told from--promised, actually,

167
00:11:04,197 --> 00:11:06,965
that any of the applied
mathematical results

168
00:11:06,967 --> 00:11:08,333
of our findings
would be our own

169
00:11:08,335 --> 00:11:10,835
and they would not
be classified.

170
00:11:10,837 --> 00:11:12,003
They'd be government
purpose rights,

171
00:11:12,005 --> 00:11:13,204
but that's it, right?

172
00:11:13,206 --> 00:11:15,040
He changed that
somewhere along the way.

173
00:11:15,042 --> 00:11:17,876
Second of all, to assume
that any of us as mathematicians

174
00:11:17,878 --> 00:11:20,278
can sufficiently gauge
the real-world implications

175
00:11:20,280 --> 00:11:22,213
of this project, it's--

176
00:11:22,215 --> 00:11:23,815
[chuckles]
It's hubris.

177
00:11:23,817 --> 00:11:25,116
I mean, it's--it's--

178
00:11:25,118 --> 00:11:27,252
it's just hubris.

179
00:11:27,254 --> 00:11:30,055
- Wow.

180
00:11:30,057 --> 00:11:33,391
How do you ever get a date
with such an academic mind?

181
00:11:33,393 --> 00:11:35,126
- I'm not sure I understand
what you're suggesting.

182
00:11:35,128 --> 00:11:37,295
- I simply dazzle them
with my card tricks.

183
00:11:37,297 --> 00:11:39,964
I mean, come on, guys,
this is...

184
00:11:39,966 --> 00:11:43,068
I feel like this is the argument
that evolutionary scientists

185
00:11:43,070 --> 00:11:45,470
have over steak dinner
and a glass of wine, right?

186
00:11:45,472 --> 00:11:47,472
It's--one solves
one problem,

187
00:11:47,474 --> 00:11:48,840
and the other one
looks back and says,

188
00:11:48,842 --> 00:11:50,141
"well,
what was before that?"

189
00:11:50,143 --> 00:11:51,342
And then,
"well, what was before that?

190
00:11:51,344 --> 00:11:53,178
What was before that?"
I mean...

191
00:11:53,180 --> 00:11:55,180
How do we get our minds
around something like that?

192
00:11:55,182 --> 00:11:56,915
- Why don't you read
my addendum?

193
00:11:56,917 --> 00:11:58,917
- I did,
and I find your assumptions

194
00:11:58,919 --> 00:12:00,885
to be inadequate,
among other things.

195
00:12:00,887 --> 00:12:02,887
- I don't think anyone
is saying here

196
00:12:02,889 --> 00:12:04,889
that we can accurately
forecast

197
00:12:04,891 --> 00:12:06,057
the implications
of our research

198
00:12:06,059 --> 00:12:08,026
50 years from now,

199
00:12:08,028 --> 00:12:10,028
if I can understand
what you're trying to say.

200
00:12:10,030 --> 00:12:11,496
Just like Oppenheimer
and fermi

201
00:12:11,498 --> 00:12:13,164
couldn't possibly
predict the consequences

202
00:12:13,166 --> 00:12:14,999
of the Los Alamos research.

203
00:12:15,001 --> 00:12:17,202
- This also begs the question
of responsibility as well.

204
00:12:17,204 --> 00:12:18,803
- How could we
possibly discuss that?

205
00:12:18,805 --> 00:12:20,071
- At Los Alamos,
they didn't--

206
00:12:20,073 --> 00:12:22,807
- this...Is not Los Alamos.

207
00:12:27,046 --> 00:12:28,847
- What did you say?

208
00:12:47,233 --> 00:12:50,001
- How's your daughter doing?
She talking yet?

209
00:12:50,003 --> 00:12:53,505
- As much as I do appreciate
the smalltalk, horton,

210
00:12:53,507 --> 00:12:55,039
it feels awkwardly
out of place

211
00:12:55,041 --> 00:12:57,275
given your little
Los Alamos project.

212
00:12:57,277 --> 00:12:59,778
- Manhattan.
- What's that?

213
00:12:59,780 --> 00:13:02,280
- Freakin' brits.
It was the Manhattan project.

214
00:13:02,282 --> 00:13:04,015
- Right.

215
00:13:04,017 --> 00:13:07,152
- Yeah, yeah,
this is all s.C.I. Classified.

216
00:13:07,154 --> 00:13:10,021
So, you know, if you
divulge anything, the NSA--

217
00:13:10,023 --> 00:13:11,422
I think that's who
we've got over there--

218
00:13:11,424 --> 00:13:13,158
they'll, uh,
they'll assassinate you.

219
00:13:13,160 --> 00:13:14,425
Probably torture you first.

220
00:13:14,427 --> 00:13:16,194
- Oh, very charming.

221
00:13:16,196 --> 00:13:18,496
Guess I should put away
my spy camera then.

222
00:13:18,498 --> 00:13:19,497
- [Chuckles]

223
00:13:19,499 --> 00:13:21,065
"But, uh, but,

224
00:13:21,067 --> 00:13:22,567
"Mr. president,
he'll see everything.

225
00:13:22,569 --> 00:13:24,235
He'll see the big board!"

226
00:13:24,237 --> 00:13:25,870
- Precisely the idea.

227
00:13:25,872 --> 00:13:28,106
Where the bloody hell
is Los Alamos, anyway?

228
00:13:28,108 --> 00:13:30,375
- Ah, it's new Mexico.
The desert.

229
00:13:30,377 --> 00:13:32,477
- Hmm. What's it like
to live in the desert?

230
00:13:32,479 --> 00:13:34,212
I do wonder.
- How should I know?

231
00:13:34,214 --> 00:13:35,547
I'm from South Philly.

232
00:13:35,549 --> 00:13:39,317
- Either way, this is certainly
not Los Alamos.

233
00:13:39,319 --> 00:13:41,019
- Wait, what'd you say?

234
00:13:41,021 --> 00:13:42,554
- Hmm? What,
"this is certainly not Los--"

235
00:13:42,556 --> 00:13:44,022
- no, no, no.
Before that.

236
00:13:44,024 --> 00:13:45,590
- Oh. I do wonder
what it's like

237
00:13:45,592 --> 00:13:47,992
to, you know, live in a--
- right, right.

238
00:13:47,994 --> 00:13:49,394
Live in a desert.

239
00:13:52,298 --> 00:13:54,599
Hugh, what are some
characteristics

240
00:13:54,601 --> 00:13:57,435
of a desert?

241
00:13:57,437 --> 00:13:58,469
- It's hot.

242
00:13:58,471 --> 00:14:00,271
- Right, yeah, and what else?

243
00:14:00,273 --> 00:14:02,874
- No water.
No rain.

244
00:14:02,876 --> 00:14:06,311
Cactuses or--cactus.
Cacti.

245
00:14:06,313 --> 00:14:09,380
- Sand.
- Sure.

246
00:14:09,382 --> 00:14:14,085
- Millions of grains of sand.

247
00:14:14,087 --> 00:14:16,054
What if I, uh,
I took something,

248
00:14:16,056 --> 00:14:18,122
like a-a quid coin, okay?

249
00:14:18,124 --> 00:14:20,124
And I buried it in the sand.

250
00:14:20,126 --> 00:14:21,559
It's buried,
you have no idea where it is,

251
00:14:21,561 --> 00:14:22,961
and I ask you to find it.

252
00:14:22,963 --> 00:14:24,028
How long would that
take you?

253
00:14:24,030 --> 00:14:25,496
- [Scoffs]
Well--

254
00:14:25,498 --> 00:14:27,298
- years, right?
I mean, millions of years,

255
00:14:27,300 --> 00:14:28,466
if the desert
were big enough.

256
00:14:28,468 --> 00:14:29,601
- Sure.

257
00:14:29,603 --> 00:14:32,604
- What if I melted the sand?

258
00:14:32,606 --> 00:14:37,008
Took all the sand in the desert
and melted it.

259
00:14:38,611 --> 00:14:41,279
Glass.

260
00:14:41,281 --> 00:14:45,016
The whole desert
becomes one big sheet of glass.

261
00:14:45,018 --> 00:14:47,151
So now, finding the coin
is easy, right?

262
00:14:47,153 --> 00:14:50,154
You just--
you see it floating there.

